  "fullDescription": "Moksha (Sanskrit: ‡§Æ‡•ã‡§ï‡•ç‡§∑, also called mukti or kaivalya) is the ultimate goal of human existence in Hinduism - liberation from samsara, the endless cycle of birth, death, and rebirth. It represents freedom from all bondage, suffering, and limitation, and the realization of one's true nature as eternal, infinite consciousness (Atman/Brahman). Different philosophical schools describe moksha differently: in Advaita Vedanta, it is the realization of non-duality between Atman and Brahman; in Dvaita Vedanta, it is eternal loving communion with God; in Yoga, it is kaivalya (isolation of purusha from prakriti). Moksha is achieved through various paths including jnana (knowledge), bhakti (devotion), karma yoga (selfless action), and raja yoga (meditation). It is considered one of the four purusharthas (goals of life), and unlike the other three (dharma, artha, kama), moksha represents the ultimate, transcendent goal. Upon attaining moksha, one is freed from karma, desire, and rebirth, experiencing eternal bliss, peace, and union with the divine.",
