      "symbolism": "Moksha symbolizes absolute freedom - freedom from ignorance, suffering, desire, karma, and the endless cycle of rebirth. It represents the fulfillment of the soul's deepest longing for infinite being, consciousness, and bliss (sat-chit-ananda). The breaking of chains often symbolizes moksha, representing liberation from bondage. The ocean symbolizes moksha in some traditions - individual souls (drops) merging with the infinite (ocean). A bird freed from its cage symbolizes the soul liberated from bodily limitations. Moksha as the fourth purushartha (beyond dharma, artha, kama) represents transcendence of all worldly goals.",
      "culturalSignificance": "Moksha gives ultimate meaning and direction to Hindu spiritual life. The concept has inspired countless seekers to renounce worldly pursuits and dedicate themselves to spiritual realization. Institutions like sannyasa (renunciation) exist specifically for those single-mindedly pursuing moksha. The belief that moksha is possible motivates spiritual practice and ethical living. Different schools and gurus offer various paths to moksha, creating rich diversity in Hindu spirituality. The concept has influenced Buddhism (nirvana), Jainism, and Sikhism. In modern times, the pursuit of moksha continues to inspire millions while also being reinterpreted in contemporary contexts."
